  "relevant_summary": "Evidence reports mixed outcomes when livestock numbers are increased: high livestock densities were associated with declines in common heather cover at UK sites and lower dwarf shrub cover in grazed areas in the Netherlands, while a randomized, replicated, paired, controlled study in the USA found no change in shrub cover [1628]. In France, cattle-grazed areas had higher cover of non\u2011ericaceous shrubs but lower cover of ericaceous shrubs, and two studies in the UK and Netherlands found mixed effects on shrub and heather cover [1628]. Plant diversity responses varied: three site comparisons in France, the Netherlands and Greece found more plant species in grazed areas than ungrazed, a Belgian before\u2011and\u2011after study found no change after introducing grazing, and a replicated before\u2011and\u2011after study in the Netherlands found a decrease in plant species number [1628]. Heather regeneration responses were mixed: a Netherlands before\u2011and\u2011after study recorded increased numbers of common heather and cross\u2011leaved heath seedlings, while two UK site comparisons reported declines in common heather cover at higher stocking densities [1628]. Structural and ground\u2011layer effects included decreased overall vegetation height in a Netherlands before\u2011and\u2011after study and reduced grass height when pony numbers increased in a Spanish heathland [1628]. Ground\u2011layer composition often shifted toward graminoids: a North\u2011Western Europe systematic review concluded higher grazing intensity increased grass cover relative to heather, and studies in the Netherlands and France found higher grass and sedge cover in high\u2011density grazed areas than ungrazed; however, a randomized, replicated, paired, controlled USA study found grass and herb cover decreased with more livestock, and other UK/Netherlands studies reported mixed effects on grass and herbaceous species [1628].",
